          "comments": [
            {
              "originalPosition": 13,
              "body": "````suggestion\n The DUT boundary for all measurements in this document is defined as the NIC-to-NIC Ethernet fabric segment \u2014 specifically, the path from the point of packet transmission by the source NIC Ethernet port to the point of packet reception at the destination NIC Ethernet port.\n````",
              "createdAt": "2026-03-24T16:12:26Z",
              "updatedAt": "2026-03-24T16:12:27Z"
            },
            {
              "originalPosition": 39,
              "body": "````suggestion\n* **KV Cache Transfer Network:**\n\n````",
              "createdAt": "2026-03-24T16:12:27Z",
              "updatedAt": "2026-03-24T16:12:27Z"
            },
            {
              "originalPosition": 42,
              "body": "````suggestion\n  * NOTE ON TRANSFER PATH DECOMPOSITION: The end-to-end transfer from GPU memory to remote GPU memory traverses three segments: (1) GPU-to-NIC: PCIe/CXL (intra-node, out of scope as DUT); (2) NIC-to-NIC: Ethernet fabric (THE DUT \u2014 in scope); (3) NIC-to GPU: PCIe/CXL at destination (intra-node, out of scope as DUT).\n````",
              "createdAt": "2026-03-24T16:12:27Z",
              "updatedAt": "2026-03-24T16:12:27Z"
            },
            {
              "originalPosition": 44,
              "body": "````suggestion\n    Benchmarking procedures in Sections 5 and 6 measure fabric-segment latency and throughput exclusively.  When end-to-end measurements are reported (e.g., TTFT decomposition), the intra-node segments MUST be labelled separately.\n````",
              "createdAt": "2026-03-24T16:12:27Z",
              "updatedAt": "2026-03-24T16:12:27Z"
            }
          ]
        }
      ]
    },
